<document>
	<title>Cystic fibrosis heterozygote detection: a family study.</title>

	<author>Danes-B-S.</author>
	<author>Beck-B.</author>
	<author>Flensborg-E-W.</author>

	<source>Clin-Genet. 1975 Jul. 8(1). P 85-91.</source>

	<abstract>Family studies have been done to determine if the phenotypes
   described for the cystic fibrosis (CF) cultured cell reliably
   detected the CF gene. Two culture phenotypes were studied in culture
   derived from consecutive generations in four CF families: (1) cystic
   fibrosis factor (CFF) in the medium of short-term white blood cell
   cultures assayed by a modified oyster ciliary test and (2) the three
   characteristics of cultured skin fibroblasts (metachromasia without
   alcianophilia at 0.3 M MgCl2, CFF in the culture medium and metabolic
   cooperation with normal fibroblasts). As CF is an autosomal recessive
   disorder, the family offered a test unit for determining the
   specificity of these cell phenotypes for the CF gene. On the basis of
   detecting the CF culture phenotypes in the homozygote and obligatory
   heterozygotes, the parents, and their segregation in consecutive
   generations, detection of the CF gene was not possible in the white
   blood cell cultures, but was possible in the skin fibroblast
   cultures.</abstract>

